.TH STIME 2 "24 July 1993" "Linux 0.99.11" "Linux Programmer's Manual"
.SH NAME
stime \- set time
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include <time.h>
.sp
.BI "int stime(time_t *" t );
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBstime\fP sets the system's idea of the time and date.  Time, pointed
to by \fIt\fP, is measured in seconds from 00:00:00 GMT January 1, 1970.
\fBstime()\fP may only be executed by the super user.
.SH "RETURN VALUE"
On success, zero is returned.  On error, \-1 is returned, and
.I errno
is set appropriately.
.SH ERRORS
.TP 0.8i
.B EPERM
The caller is not the super-user.
.SH "CONFORMING TO"
SVID, AT&T, X/OPEN
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR date (1)
